Human Tasks are the basic building blocks of a Business Case definition. From a user perspective, they are actionable items within a Business Case workflow, which may prompt the user to select a file or provide input in order to advance the Business Case Instance. This article takes a closer look at Human Tasks, exploring how they are managed and edited within the Workplace 2 environment.

Human Tasks are visualized in Workplace 2 in two ways:

- **As table entries in the Tasks tab:** For monitoring and organizational purposes

- **As actionable items in the task editor:** For providing input and advancing the Business Case Instance

Read on to find out more about the two views and how to work with Human Tasks in Workplace 2.

## Tasks
The Tasks tab provides the main overview of all Human Tasks. It consists of two areas:

- Top **toolbar** with search filters and bulk action buttons (only visible when at least one checkbox is selected)

- **Table** overview containing all Human Tasks in currently instantiated Business Case Instances

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The following actions can be performed on a task from the Tasks tab, depending on its current status:

- **Start**: Opens the task in the task editor

- **Assign**: Assigns the task to a specific user

- **Terminate**: Terminates the task and moves both the task and its Business Case Instance into status **Terminated**

> Tip: Perform actions from the details page

All actions which can be performed from one of the table overviews of Workplace 2 are also available in the details page.

The table in the Tasks tab contains the following columns:

Field

Description

**State**

Status of the task:

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) **Created**: The task has been initiated.

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) **Open**: The task has been created, but not started yet.

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) **Locked**: The task is locked by a user.

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) **Completed**: The task has been completed, but not all system watchers have successfully finished yet.

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) **Finished**: The task has been completed successfully.

- ![](data:image/png;base64,) **Terminated**: The task has been terminated manually by a user or by the system due to an error.

**Created at**

Creation time of the task

**Assignee**

Assignee of the current task

**Potential Assignee**

Potential assignee(s) of the current task

**Task ID**

Unique ID of the currently open task in the Business Case Instance

**Description**

Name of the task

**Business Case ID**

Unique ID of the Business Case

**Process Element**

Technical name of the element within the Business Case process (Process Engine-specific)

**Execution ID**

ID of the execution instance (Process Engine-specific)

**Finished at**

Finishing time of the task (only if the task has the status **Finished**)

**Last updated at**

Date and time at which the task was most recently updated

**Priority**

Priority of the task

**Supervisors**

Supervisors of the task

**Type**

Task type (Process Engine-specific)

> Tip: Configure table columns

To display or hide specific columns from the table, click the three-dot icon in the right corner of the header row and select or deselect the desired columns.

## Task editor
The task editor is the core work interface of Workplace 2. It displays all steps within the workflow and provides the interface for editing the current step.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The task editor consists of two main areas:

- Left **sidebar** displaying all Human Tasks within the Business Case Instance and navigational buttons

- Large **workspace** for editing Human Tasks

The task editor can be seen in action in [Getting started: How to open and complete a Business Case](/doxee-platform/docs/workplace-6-6-getting-started-1).

## Find a Human Task
Each Human Task coming from instantiated Business Case Instances can be located individually through its **Task ID**.

To locate a specific Human Task, navigate to the **Tasks tab**. This tab displays all instantiated Human Tasks in a fully searchable and sortable table view.

The table contents can be refined using the following filters:

![Table displaying task details including state, assignee, and priority information.](data:image/png;base64,)

- **State**

- **Created at**

- **Assignee** (exact-match text search)

- **Potential Assignees** (exact-match text search)

- **Task ID** (exact-match text search)

- **Description** (exact-match text search)

- **Business Case ID** (exact-match text search)

- **Process Element** (exact-match text search)

- **Execution ID** (exact-match text search)

- **Finished at**

- **Last updated at**

- **Priority**

- **Supervisors** (exact-match text search)

- **Type** (exact-match text search)

## Edit a Human Task in the task editor
To work on a Human Task, it must be opened in the **task editor**. This can be done in one of the following ways:

- **Start a new Business Case**: Locate the desired Business Case definition and click **Start**. The newly created Business Case Instance will be automatically opened in the task editor, and the first task in the workflow will be displayed.

- **Continue an existing Business Case Instance**: Locate an already created Business Case Instance and click **Continue**. The task editor will be opened, and the latest open task in the workflow will be displayed.

- **Open an existing Human Task**: Locate an already created Human Task and click **Start**. The task editor will be opened, and the selected task will be displayed.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

All necessary input for the task can be provided in the large editing area on the right side. Once the input is complete, use the navigational buttons in the sidebar to advance the Business Case Instance to the next step in the workflow.

> Tip: Example Business Case Instance

A walkthrough of a typical workflow can be seen in [Getting started: How to open and complete a Business Case](/doxee-platform/docs/workplace-6-6-getting-started-1).

## Save and close a Human Task
Sometimes it may be necessary to save the workflow progress and navigate away from the task editor, for example because another user must approve the next step in the workflow. This can be done from the **task editor** interface:

- Click the ![](data:image/png;base64,) icon on the top of the sidebar. The saving dialog is displayed.

- Select one of the options:

**Unlock the task and save changes**: Saves the changes and leaves the task unlocked for other users

- **Unlock the task and discard changes**: Discards the changes and leaves the task unlocked for other users

- **Leave task locked for you**: Saves the changes and locks the task for the current user

![Options for leaving a running business case with task management choices displayed.](data:image/png;base64,)

The task editor is closed and the window is redirected back to the **Tasks** tab.

## Assign a Human Task to another user
The assignee of a task is the specific user who can open the task in the task editor. Each task can have only one current assignee, but several potential assignees. Potential assignees are users who have the necessary user rights to check out the task and are therefore eligible as assignees.

The assignee is first selected automatically based on the specific configurations of the Business Case definition. The task can later be reassigned manually in one of the following ways:

- **From the Business Case Instance:** Assign the latest task in a Business Case Instance to a different user

- **From the Tasks tab:** Assign a specific task to a different user

For both cases, the workflow to change the assignee of a Human Task is the same:

- Navigate to the Business Case Instances or Tasks tab, respectively, and locate the specific item which should be reassigned.

> Changing the assignee of a Business Case Instance

When the assignee of a Business Case Instance is changed, the change is only applied to the latest step in the workflow.

- Click the status icon of the Human Task or Business Case Instance. A toolbar with action buttons is displayed.![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Click **Assign** and enter the username of the new assignee.![Task assignment pop-up dialog showing fields for assignee and action buttons.](data:image/png;base64,)

- Confirm the action by clicking **Save**.

The Human Task is now assigned to the new user. A warning message is shown if the selected user doesnt have the required rights to edit the task.

> Tip: View all potential assignees for a task

If you want to check which users a particular task can be assigned to based on their user privileges, locate the Human Task you want to reassign, for example in the Tasks tab or through its details page. The table column **Potential Assignees** contains a list of all users which have the necessary user privileges to edit this task.

## Terminate a Human Task
A Human Task can be terminated manually in one of the following ways:

- **From the Business Task Instance:** Terminate the parent [Business Case Instance](/doxee-platform/docs/workplace-6-6-business-case-instances-2). Doing so also automatically terminates the latest Human Task in the workflow and moves both items into the status **Terminated**.

- **From the Human Task:** Locate the desired Human Task and click **Terminate** in the toolbar.

- **From the task editor:** Click **Cancel** at the bottom of the left navigation bar. (Note that the navigation buttons in the task editor are highly customizable and may diverge significantly from the examples depicted here.)

> Irreversible action

Terminating a Human Task is an irreversible action. Once a Human Task has been terminated, both it and its parent Business Case Instance will be moved into the status **Terminated**. Human Tasks or Business Case Instances in this status cant be reopened or reassigned.

## View the details of a Human Task
The details page of a Human Task provides information and action buttons to manage it. It can be accessed in one of the following ways:

- Click the **Task ID** in the Tasks tab

- Open the **URL **of the task details page

> Tip: How to get the URL of a Human Task

Every Workplace item can be accessed through a unique URL that leads to its details page. To copy the URL, open the details panel of the desired item and click the **Copy link** button.

The details page consists of two areas:

- **Toolbar **with action buttons at the top

- **Information** about the Human Task

![Task details showing status, assignees, and timestamps.](data:image/png;base64,)

The following actions are available for a Human Task:

- **Start**: Starts the task

- **Assign**: Assign the task to a particular user

- **Terminate**: Terminates the task

- **Copy link**: Copies the URL of the task to the clipboard

The detail page of a task within a Business Case Instance contains the following information:

Field

Description

**State**

Status of the task

**Priority**

Priority of the task

**Business Case**

Name of the Business Case

**Current Assignee**

Username of the current assignee of the task

**Potentias Assignees**

Username(s) of the potential assignee(s) of the task

**Created by**

Username of the creator of the task

**Created at**

Date and time of creation

**Last updated at**

Date and time of the latest update of the task

**Finished at**

Date and time at which the task was moved into the status **Finished**

**Process ID**

Unique ID of the process

**Task ID**

Unique ID of the task

**Blacklisted users**

Users which are blocked from editing this task

Business Cases are interactive processes which are started and completed from Workplace. A Business Case typically consists of one or several Human Tasks, which require user input in order to advance the process. An open Business Case is called a Business Case Instance.
